Having played both games, I'd say that I enjoy this less than the 2nd one. I know it's the sequel but firstly: the lack of melee takedowns, combined with the absurdly overpowered enemies make this game throat-splittingly difficult. Secondly: the vision range feels way too short for the map size which is often way too big. Thirdly, the disguise suit doesn't work since there is no "walking" (game only allows running). The only redeeming point is that the guns are better in this game than the 2nd.

I am so glad they went with charging an upfront cost for this game. This could have easily been a free-to-play game with microtransactions, but the fact that there are no microtransactions improves the gameplay experience tremendously. It is so nice to feel respected as a player, and not feel like they are trying to take advantage of human psychology to squeeze money out of players. The game itself runs very smoothly, and the touch controls work really really well, which always surprises me.

Wow, it is such a pleasure to be able to buy a license outright. I'm so sick of IAP this and IAP that.  When IAP was first introduced, I swore I would not use it. Then, I started using it for developers that did it right (no repeat or consumable purchases), but many of those developers started sneaking in others purchase, so much so, I've stopped using IAP once again. Just sell a license! Write a game, sell it, then move on to your next project (maintaining current titles when there is a need); this formula has worked for years, until some low-life decided they wanted more and started fleecing their customers with IAP. It makes sense for truly in-depth, persistent world MMOs, but not for half-baked mobile games. It's a racket. Thanks Pixelbite, you have a new, devoted customer. When's your next game coming out? I'll buy it immediately, if you stick to this purchasing model! Sorry folks, my diatribe is done, but do yourself a favor and get this game! They took a chance supporting their customers, so let's support them - it's the only way we'll get more high-quality IAP-free apps. DEVELOPER: Unfortunately, you decided to go the IAP route with your new title - no thanks! I'll pass....
replyContent:
Next game - XENOWERK! and it's launching within the next couple of weeks.
visit our website www.pixelbite.se for furtehr info.

Would like to see multiple difficulty levels added (casual to hard) and the ability to save in-level, but other than these slight omissions this game is superbly done. Highly recommended. Edit: 2 things eventually ruined it for me: 1) the addition of timers to levels - i HATE HATE HATE timers. 2) being killed 5 times, once every 2.6 seconds, by minibosses gets discouraging very quickly. i've had enough of that. It was fun so long as i got to choose my own pace, but not once a timer starts tripling my blood pressure.

content: A very polished top down shooter with excellent graphics and satisfying, challenging gameplay, with a forgiving checkpoint system that lets less skilled players progress while ultimately rewarding better players and those replaying levels with more useful unlockable equipment and weapons. However, despite the emphasis on "tactics", missions can often be completed quickly Rambo-style using the right weapons, while the limited options to silently take down enemies leaves few reasons to go in stealthily. Typical for the genre on mobile, the virtual controls can also be fiddly at times, and the game has heated up my phone far more than any game I've played on it before. Aside from those minor gripes, with its long campaign and its emphasis on replayability, there's still a lot of fun and enjoyment to be had with Space Marshals. Highly recommended.
